.SH "FB_FILE"
.sp
Whenever a framebuffer is needed, and the \fB\-F\fP option has not
been specified, the environment variable \f(CRFB_FILE\fP is checked for
the device to use.  The format of this variable is either
\fI[hostname:]/dev/device_name[num]\fP or \fIUNIX_path\fP, the pathname of a
disk file to be used as a "virtual framebuffer". \fIHostname\fP is the
name of a remote machine if the remote framebuffer interface is being
used. When a local display device is being specified, the \fIhostname\fP
should not be specified, for performance reasons; just the special
string \fIdevice_name\fP is used to select a particular type of
framebuffer. \fINum\fP is type dependent and can either mean a display
number or select some options for that type. Note that for security
reasons, it is not permitted to access a disk file via the remote
interface.
.sp
If \f(CRFB_FILE\fP is not set, the default for your system will be
used.
.sp
The use of \fI/dev/\fP before the \fIdevice_name\fP is simply to
distinguish them from filenames.  See the end of the
\fBlibfb\fP(3) manual page for a list of the device
names and the meanings of any \fInum\fP parameters they may take, and for
a more detailed discussion.
.SH "OPTIONS"
.sp
A convention exists for the options used on most of the utilities
provided. Random options are usually lower case. Options which could
specify either a screen or file size are, by convention, lower case
for file information, and upper case for screen information. Here\(cqs a
list of some of the common options you may encounter:
.sp
\fB\-i\fP
.RS 4
Inverse flag.  Pretend origin is in upper left corner of
screen, for that good old\-fashioned fourth\-quadrant behavior.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-c\fP
.RS 4
Various.  Typically means clear the screen first.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-z\fP
.RS 4
Various.  Typically means zoom\-in on current area of display.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-s\fP \fIsquare_file_size\fP
.RS 4
\fIWARNING:\fP Behavior is undefined when the
\fB\-s\fP flag is used in conjunction with the \fB\-w\fP or \fB\-n\fP
flags.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-w\fP \fIfile_width\fP
.RS 4
\fIWARNING:\fP Behavior is undefined when the
\fB\-S\fP flag is used in conjunction with the \fB\-W\fP or \fB\-N\fP
flags.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-W\fP \fIscreen_width\fP
.RS 4
specifies the number of bytes per sample, where
the flag, where the \fI\(rs#\fP character is a literal "pound" or "sharp"
sign character, typically found over the numeral "3" on ANSI
keyboards. Several programs (like pixrect) can operate on data samples
of arbitrary width. For example, a \fBpix\fP(5)
format file can often be treated like a \fBbw\fP(5)
format file with a width of three bytes per sample.
.RE
.SH "TAPE FORMAT"
.sp
When dealing with large collections of images, as might be needed for
making a movie, it frequently becomes desirable to deal with magnetic
tapes. Some of the early \fBpix\fP(5) tools contained
built\-in knowledge of the tape format. While this aberrant early
design has been corrected in favor of using tape\-oriented programs
such as \fBdd\fP(1) in pipelines with the image tools,
our "standard" image format remains.
.sp
Regardless of image resolution, all tape records are 24k bytes
long. If an image does not occupy an integral number of tape records,
the last record is padded out. For example, NTSC images in 640x480
format use 37.5 records per image. The
\fBfiles\-tape\fP(1) utility is helpful in
performing this function.
.sp
